What are regular expressions?

Regular expressions are b␀a sequence of characters that define a search patternb␀ 1 similar to the [command + f] function you use to find text in a pdf or word document. You could think of regular expressions like playing a game of charades. Assume a player grabs a playing card with an image of a person reading a book. Their task is to pantomine this action (reading a book) so that other players can guess what they are doing. Through the use of physical expressions and symbols, the player with the card is helping the other players guess what playing card they got. In this analogy, the player with the playing card is you the user and the players trying to guess your card is your machine or computer. As the user, you use regular expressions or special characters to tell your computer what characters you are looking for in a text.


source: https://www.wikihow.it/Giocare-a-Sciarada

Regular expressions 101

Some common regular expression patterns include (not inclusive):

  • Anchors
  • Quantifiers
  • Groups and ranges
  • Character classes
  • POSIX
    source: https://cheatography.com/davechild/cheat-sheets/regular-expressions/

Regular expression characters

Select each tab

Anchors

Character Description
^ Start of string, or start of line in multi-line pattern
\A Start of string
$ End of string, or end of line in multi-line pattern
\Z End of string
\b Word boundary
\B Not word boundary
\< Start of word
\> End of word

The grep and grepl functions are part of Base R. Notice the difference between their output. grepl returns a logical vector (TRUE, FALSE) whereas grep returns numbers which represent the index location of the pattern. I created this character vector and assigned it the name a. There are five character objects inside this vector. The grep function tells R to look for the pattern where the object starts with the letter a (b␀^ab␀), returning the values 1, 2, 5.

a <- c("aabd", "aacd", "caad", "cbde", "abcb")

grepl("^a", a) #Logical vector
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
grep("^a", a) #indexed location 
## [1] 1 2 5

Give it a try. Use the grep function to look for instances in this vector that end with the letter d. What regular expression character would you use?

Quantifiers

Character Description Code Result
* 0 or more {3} Exactly 3
+ 1 or more {3,} 3 or more
? 0 or 1 {3,5} 3, 4 or 5
\ Escape character \s white space

We use quantifiers to specify the number of times we want to search for a particular pattern.

b <- c("aaa", "abc", "bca", "dd c", "abbc")

In the first grepl function below we use the + to search for patterns in the b vector where the beginning of a string begins with an a one or more times.

grepl("^a+", b) #searching for pattern where objects start with a 1 or more times
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE

The second grepl function is searching for the letter a exactly three times.

grepl("a{3}", b) #searching for pattern that has exactly 3 a's
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

Lastly, notice how we use two \\ backward slashes to escape the letter s suggesting we are referring to white space and not the literal letter s. More on this later.

grepl("\\sc", b) #searching for pattern that has a white space followed by a c
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE

Give it a try, Use the grepl function to look for instances in this vector that have 1 or more instances of the letter b. What regular expression character would you use?

Groups and ranges

Character Description
. Any character except new line ()
(a|b) a or b
(b␀&) Group
(?:b␀&) Passive (non-capturing) group
[abc] Range (a or b or c)
[^abc] Not (a or b or c)
[a-z] Lower case letter from a to q
[A-Z] Upper case letter from A to Q
[0-7] Digit from 0 to 7
\x Group/subpattern number b␀xb␀

We use grouping characters to specify a range of characters.

c <- c("Is", "it", "Saturday", "today", "?")

We use parentheses and a | to search for a or o.

grepl("(a|o)", c) #search for a or o in a pattern
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE

The second grepl function with square brackets indicates a range. In the code below, we are searching for the letters a, i, or o.

grepl("[aio]", c)
## [1] FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE

The square brackets with the range from a-z indicate any lowercase alphabetical letters.

grepl("[a-z]", c)
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE

Give it a try. Use the grepl function to look for instances in this vector that begin with the letter i or end with the letter y. What regular expression character would you use?

Character classes

Character Description
\c Control character
\s White space
\S Not white space
\d Digit
\D Not digit
\w Word
\W Not word
\x Hexadecimal digit
\O Octal digit 
d <- c("25 days", "Hi, my name is", "What is your name?")

Using the escape character followed by the letter s and then the letter d, we are searching for a white space and a letter d.

grepl("\\sd", d) 
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE

Combining some characters we learned earlier like the ^ , +, and the \\s, we are searching a character string that begins with a one or more digits followed by a white space.

grepl("^\\d+\\s", d)
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE

Give it a try. Use the grepl function to search for the word name.

POSIX

Character Description
[:upper:] Upper case letters
[:lower:] Lower case letters
[:alpha:] All letters
[:alnum:] Digits and letters
[:digit:] Digits
[:xdigit:] Hexadecimal digits
[:punct:] Punctuation
[:blank:] Space and tab
[:space:] Blank characters
[:cntrl:] Control characters
[:graph:] Printed characters
[:print:] Printed characters and spaces
[:word:] Digits, letters and underscore

The POSIX or b␀Portable Operating System Interface for uniXb␀ is a collection of standards that define some of the functionality that a (UNIX) operating system should support 2. As you may have noticed, some of the functions from POSIX have similar functionality to functions we have learned. For example, \\d and [:digit:] both search for digits.

Student exercise

Now it is time to apply what we have learned. Later on in the course we will learn how to use APIs and stream data from the internet (Twitter & LinkedIn). For the purpose of this lecture on regular expressions we will simplify our approach. We ask you to open your internet browser and google lyrics to your favorite song or song you like. In this example, we googled b␀all of me lyricsb␀. We then copied the first ten lines and pasted them in a code chunk below. Notice that we separate each line by quotes followed by a comma.

Instructions

  1. Google song lyrics of your choice
  2. Copy the fist ten lines
  3. Paste in a code chunk
  4. Clean up your pasted text so that every line is surrounded by quotes and separated by a comma. Do not forget to wrap that around c()
  5. Assign to an object (ex. song)

Task:
For each of the common regular expression characters we reviewed (e.g.B Anchors, Quantifiers, Groups and ranges, and Character classes), choose two characters and practice applying them to your lyrics. You should have 8 regular expression functions by the end of this exercise.

Ex.

song <- c("What would I do without your smart mouth",
          "Drawing me in, and you kicking me out",
          "You got my head spinning, no kidding, I can't pin you down",
          "What's going on in that beautiful mind",
          "I'm on your magical mystery ride",
          "And I'm so dizzy, don't know what hit me, but I'll be alright",
          "My head's underwater",
          "But I'm breathing fine",
          "You're crazy and I'm out of my mind",
          "Cause all all all ...")


grep("all+|dizzy", song)  
## [1]  6 10
grep("(^D|n$)", song)
## [1] 2 3
